name: 03-Exploratory Analytics
content:
EXPLORATORY ANALYTICS OF DATA


HUMAN ERROR

Occurrence of Human Error

The pie chart shows that 61.4% of the occurrences did not have human error, while 38.6% did. This suggests that human error is a significant factor in a minority of cases.



Distribution Of Experience of Inspector in Months

The bar chart shows the distribution of inspectors' experience levels in months. The majority of inspectors have between 33.8-37.9 months and 37.9-42.0 months of experience. This suggests that the organization may have a significant number of inspectors with mid-level experience.


 Distribution of Shifts w.r.t Inspection Error

The bar chart shows the distribution of inspection errors across different shifts. Night shifts have a significantly higher number of errors compared to day shifts. This suggests that there might be factors related to night shifts that contribute to a higher incidence of human error.


Count With/Without Machine Break

The bar chart shows that machine breaks significantly increase the likelihood of human errors. There are more errors during machine breaks than during non-break periods. This suggests that machine breaks may be a contributing factor to human errors.


Experience of Worker

The pie chart shows the distribution of human errors across different experience levels of workers. Workers with 1-10 years of experience have the highest percentage of human errors (43%), followed by those with 31-40 years of experience (29.5%). This suggests that experience may not be a strong predictor of human error reduction.


Inspector Experience Vs Defect Counts

The bar chart shows the relationship between inspector experience and the number of defects found. Inspectors with 1-10 years of experience tend to find more defects, both when they make errors and when they don't. This suggests that experience may not be a strong predictor of defect detection accuracy.


Raw Material Degrade


Distribution of Time Span of Material

The pie chart shows the distribution of time spans for raw materials. The majority of raw materials have a time span of 0-5 days (55%), followed by 5-10 days (31.6%) and 10-15 days (21.4%). This indicates that a significant portion of raw materials are used within a short timeframe.

Distribution of Material Duration w.r.t Degraded Status

The bar chart shows the distribution of raw material durations with respect to their degraded status. It appears that raw materials with a duration of 1-5 days have the highest proportion of non-degraded items, while those with a duration of 10-15 days have the highest proportion of degraded items. This suggests that longer storage durations may increase the likelihood of material degradation.


Distribution of Degraded Material

The pie chart shows that 51.1% of raw materials were not degraded, while 48.9% were degraded. This indicates that a significant portion of raw materials remain in good condition.

Sensor Failure

Distribution of Sensor Reading

The pie chart shows the distribution of sensor readings. 70.8% of the readings are 1, while 29.2% are 0. This indicates that the sensor is more likely to register a value of 1 compared to 0.


Production Time Trends

The pie chart shows the distribution of production times. The majority of production times fall within the 1-15 minute range (70.8%), followed by 15-30 minutes (16.7%), 30-45 minutes (8.3%), and 45+ minutes (4.2%). This indicates that most production processes are completed within a short timeframe.



 Distribution of Production Duration With Respect to Sensor Reading Status

The bar chart shows the distribution of production durations with respect to sensor reading status. It appears that the majority of wrong sensor readings occur within the 1-15 minute period. Additionally, correct readings are more frequent in the 1-15 minute range compared to longer durations. This suggests that there might be a correlation between shorter production times and accurate sensor readings.
